	<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en">Bruno della Chiesa</h1>
	
	<div id="bodyContent" class="mw-body-content">
		<div id="siteSub" class="noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
		<div id="contentSub"></div>
		
		
		
		<div id="jump-to-nav"></div>
		<a class="mw-jump-link" href="#mw-head">Jump to navigation</a>
		<a class="mw-jump-link" href="#p-search">Jump to search</a>
		<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><div class="mw-parser-output"><p><b>Bruno della Chiesa</b> (born 7 July 1962) is a linguist of Italian, French and German descent, who describes himself as an "engaged cosmopolitan".<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> He teaches at <a href="/wiki/Harvard_University" title="Harvard University">Harvard University</a> and is considered one of the main founders of <a href="/wiki/Educational_neuroscience" title="Educational neuroscience">educational neuroscience</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> is known to have coined the terms <a href="/wiki/Educational_neuroscience#Neuromyths" title="Educational neuroscience">"neuromyth"</a> (2002)<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> and "neuro-hijacking" (2013) and has established theories on the "motivational <a href="/wiki/Vortex" title="Vortex">vortex</a>" (2007)<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> and on the “<a href="/wiki/Tesseracts" class="mw-redirect" title="Tesseracts">tesseracts</a> in the brain” (2008).<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> He also created the international science fiction festival <a href="/wiki/Utopiales" title="Utopiales">Utopiales</a>.
</p>
